explanation:
Agent A is correct. The four lines
  (void) cls;
  (void) version;
  (void) upload_data;
  (void) upload_data_size;
are expression statements that are executed but have no effect on the observable behaviour of the program; removing them would not change program semantics. That matches the definition of dead code in MISRA C 2023 Rule 2.2, so the code as written violates that rule.

(Notes: the Rule 2.2 exception for unreachable code does not apply here because these statements are reachable and executed. The Rule 2.2 note about timing means one must consider whether an otherwise effect‑free operation is relied on for timing — in this case these simple cast-to-void expressions do not provide meaningful timing behaviour and are normally emitted as no code by compilers, so that exception does not rescue them.)

Recommended remedies: remove those effect‑free statements and either omit the parameter names in the function definition for parameters that are intentionally unused (e.g. leave the parameter name out in the function definition) or mark the parameters as intentionally unused using a documented, tool-supported mechanism (for example a standard project-wide UNUSED(x) macro that expands to a compiler-supported attribute, or using a portable attribute if your toolchain supports it). If a project decides to keep the (void) cast idiom, that should be recorded as a formal deviation from Rule 2.2 with justification.
